{{incomplete|date=December 2011}} '''Occupy Berkeley''' is an ongoing series of [[Demonstration (people)|demonstrations]] in [[Berkeley, California]] based in front of a [[Bank of America]]. It is an offshoot of the [[Occupy Wall Street]] movement.
==Events== On November 9, 2011, police used violence to clear [[Sproul Plaza]], beating [[Robert Hass]], his wife [[Brenda Hillman]], faculty [[Celeste Langan]] and [[Geoffrey OâBrien]] at an Occupy Berkeley protest.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.berkeleyside.com/2011/11/14/after-oakland-eviction-occupy-focus-shifts-to-uc-berkeley/| title=After Oakland eviction, Occupy focus shifts to UC Berkeley| date=November 14, 2011| author= Tracey Taylor| work=Berkeleyside}}</ref> This use of force gained national recognition, which is controversial for many affiliated. <ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.berkeleyside.com/2011/11/11/police-use-of-force-at-occupy-cal-gets-national-attention/ | title=Police use of force at Occupy Cal gets national attention| author= Tracey Taylor| work=Berkeleyside}}</ref>
Hass wrote a ''New York Times'' opinion article about the beating.<ref>{{cite news| author=Robert Hass| title=Poet-Bashing Police| url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/20/opinion/sunday/at-occupy-berkeley-beat-poets-has-new-meaning.html?_r=3&pagewanted=all| date= November 19, 2011 | work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref>
Jim Chanin said: {{quote|"Using a baton to go through a nonviolent crowd is as inappropriate today as it was in the South when they used it to enforce segregation in the 1960s" <ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2011/11/11/MNH21LTC4D.DTL| title=UC cops' use of batons on Occupy camp questioned| authors=Will Kane, Demian Bulwa| work=San Francisco Chronicle| date=November 11, 2011}} </ref> }}
